---

<BaseLayout
  title="Fundamentals 1 — Alice Morrison"
  description="Unfolding case study: G-Tube Care in a Pediatric Patient (FUN-01)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/fundamentals/`}>Fundamentals</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Fundamentals 1 — Alice Morrison</span>
  </div>

  <!-- ── CASE HEADER ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Pediatric</span>
    <h1>Fundamentals 1 — Alice Morrison</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">G-Tube Care in a Pediatric Patient</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Alice Morrison, 7 years old, Female</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── HOW TO USE ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 1 — YOU ARRIVE AT THE BEDSIDE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You are the morning nurse on the pediatric inpatient unit. You receive handoff report and head to see your patient for the first time.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Alice Morrison</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / DOB</th><td>7 years old</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Gender</th><td>Female</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Setting</th><td>Pediatric inpatient unit</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Acute bronchitis</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Secondary Dx</th><td>Esophageal atresia with gastrostomy tube (G-tube)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergy</th><td>Review MAR</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Family</th><td>Mother present — primary caregiver and G-tube expert</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Current Medications (on MAR)</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>Gentamicin (Garamycin) 48 mg IV Piggyback Q8HRS</li>
          <li>Ampicillin IV (per order)</li>
          <li>Ranitidine (Zantac Syrup) 47 mg PO/G-tube Q12HRS</li>
          <li>Acetaminophen Suspension 100 mg/mL <span class="badge-warning">PRN</span> via G-tube (10–15 mg/kg/dose)</li>
          <li>Ibuprofen Suspension 20 mg/mL (Motrin) <span class="badge-warning">PRN</span> via G-tube (5–10 mg/kg/dose)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>
        Alice is a 7-year-old girl lying in a hospital bed. Her mother is seated at the bedside. Alice appears mildly flushed and restless. Her G-tube feeding is connected and running when you walk in, but on closer inspection you notice the dressing around the G-tube appears wet. Mother greets you anxiously.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>🔒 SWIPE Safety Assessment</h3>
    <p>Before touching the patient, perform your environmental safety check:</p>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Letter</th><th>Check</th><th>What You Find</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Siderails up</td><td>Both rails up — <span class="text-success">appropriate for pediatric patient ✓</span></td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>W</strong></td><td>Wristband on, matches chart</td><td>Present and correct — verify with 2 identifiers (name + DOB) ✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>I</strong></td><td>IV lines — site, patency, rate, label</td><td>Right hand IV access; Gentamicin IVPB infusing; assess site for redness/swelling</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Pull cord / call light within reach</td><td>Within mother's reach — child may not operate call light alone ✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Equipment — bed position, path clear</td><td>Bed in lowest position; G-tube feeding pump present; ensure room path is clear</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What initial observations concern you, and how do you introduce yourself to a 7-year-old child and her anxious mother?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Concerns on arrival:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Mildly flushed appearance — possible fever</li>
          <li>Wet dressing around G-tube — formula leakage, skin breakdown risk</li>
          <li>Mother appears anxious — she is the G-tube expert; engage her immediately</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Introducing yourself to a 7-year-old — developmental considerations:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Get down to Alice's eye level — do not stand over her</li>
          <li>"Hi Alice! My name is ___ and I'm going to be your nurse today. Is it okay if I check on you?"</li>
          <li>Verify two identifiers: name + date of birth</li>
          <li>Use simple, age-appropriate language: "I'm going to check your tummy tube"</li>
          <li>Address mother: "Hello, Mrs. Morrison. I want to make sure I understand everything about Alice's care. You clearly know her best — can you walk me through her usual routine?"</li>
          <li>Allow Alice to hold a familiar comfort object; involve her in age-appropriate choices</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ As you perform your initial assessment, a critical finding emerges…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 2 — DISCOVERING THE DISCONNECTED G-TUBE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Discovering the Disconnected G-Tube</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      As you perform your assessment you discover a critical finding that requires immediate attention.
    </p>

    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🔍 Critical Finding</h3>
      <p>
        The G-tube feeding tubing has <strong>disconnected from the G-tube</strong>. Formula has leaked onto the dressing and bed pad, saturating both. The stoma site shows formula residue and moisture. Alice's mother notices you examining the site and becomes more anxious.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌡️ Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Temperature</th><td>38.4°C (101.1°F) <span class="badge-danger">FEVER</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Heart Rate</th><td>104 bpm <span class="badge-warning">Mild tachycardia</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory Rate</th><td>22 breaths/min — within normal for age</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td>96% on room air — adequate</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood Pressure</th><td>98/62 mmHg — normal for 7-year-old</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pain</th><td>3/10 using Wong-Baker FACES scale</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🔎 Head-to-Toe Assessment Findings</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>General:</strong> Mildly flushed, restless, appears uncomfortable</li>
          <li><strong>Respiratory:</strong> RR 22, mild rhonchi bilaterally, occasional productive cough, no retractions</li>
          <li><strong>Abdomen / G-tube:</strong> <span class="badge-danger">DISCONNECTED</span> feeding tubing; saturated dressing; wet bed pad; stoma site moist with formula residue; skin around stoma appears intact but moist</li>
          <li><strong>IV site:</strong> Right hand; no redness or swelling; Gentamicin IVPB infusing</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What are your priority problems and what do you do first?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Priority problems (ranked):</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Disconnected G-tube feeding</strong> — nutrition interrupted + immediate skin breakdown risk from formula moisture</li>
          <li><strong>Fever 38.4°C</strong> — requires assessment and antipyretic administration via G-tube</li>
          <li><strong>Respiratory assessment</strong> — ongoing bronchitis requires monitoring</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Immediate action sequence:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Stop the feeding pump; clamp the G-tube tubing</li>
          <li>Assess the stoma site fully — check for skin breakdown, drainage, erythema</li>
          <li>Change the saturated dressing using clean technique</li>
          <li>Reconnect tubing securely; restart feeding after confirming placement</li>
          <li>Administer acetaminophen via G-tube for fever</li>
          <li>Continue respiratory assessment; auscultate lung sounds</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Communicate calmly to mother:</strong> "Mrs. Morrison, I can see Alice's tube feeding has disconnected. I'm going to clean up the area and reconnect it. Can you tell me how long this might have been like this? And I'd love to watch your usual technique — you know Alice's care better than anyone."</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You prepare to perform a G-tube dressing change…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 3 — G-TUBE DRESSING CHANGE AND HYGIENE CARE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>G-Tube Dressing Change and Hygiene Care</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You proceed with a complete G-tube site assessment and dressing change. Alice's mother is watching and ready to help.
    </p>

    <h3>🩹 Step-by-Step G-Tube Dressing Change Procedure</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th><th>Rationale</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1</td><td>Perform hand hygiene; don clean gloves</td><td>Infection prevention — standard precautions</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2</td><td>Explain to Alice and mother: "Alice, I'm going to clean around your tube and put on a clean dry bandage. It might feel a little cold. Is that okay?"</td><td>Age-appropriate preparation reduces anxiety; builds trust</td></tr>
        <tr><td>3</td><td>Stop the feeding pump; clamp the G-tube</td><td>Prevents additional formula leakage during dressing change</td></tr>
        <tr><td>4</td><td>Remove the saturated dressing; assess stoma site immediately</td><td>Wet dressings harbor bacteria and cause skin maceration</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5</td><td>Clean the stoma site with warm water or saline per protocol; use gentle circular motion outward from tube</td><td>Removes formula residue; reduces infection and skin irritation risk</td></tr>
        <tr><td>6</td><td>Assess stoma skin: intact but moist; no erythema, no breakdown, no granulation tissue noted</td><td>Early identification of complications prevents worsening</td></tr>
        <tr><td>7</td><td>Apply fresh, dry gauze or foam dressing split around the stoma base</td><td>Absorbs moisture; protects skin from formula contact</td></tr>
        <tr><td>8</td><td>Ensure the external bumper has 1–2 finger-width clearance</td><td>Too tight = pressure injury; too loose = tube migration risk</td></tr>
        <tr><td>9</td><td>Change wet bed pad; assist with hygiene as needed</td><td>Restores comfort; promotes dignity</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10</td><td>Reconnect feeding tubing securely to G-tube port</td><td>Prevents future disconnection</td></tr>
        <tr><td>11</td><td>Check gastric residual before restarting (aspirate gently; hold if &gt; facility policy limit)</td><td>Verifies gastric emptying; prevents aspiration</td></tr>
        <tr><td>12</td><td>Restart G-tube feeding at ordered rate</td><td>Resumes nutrition delivery</td></tr>
        <tr><td>13</td><td>Position HOB at 30–45 degrees</td><td>Reduces aspiration risk during enteral feeding</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">🔍 Stoma Site Assessment</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Assessment Parameter</th><th>Finding</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Redness / Erythema</td><td>None currently present</td><td>Continue monitoring; document baseline</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Swelling</td><td>None</td><td>No action needed</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Drainage</td><td>Formula residue (clear/milky) — from leakage</td><td>Clean thoroughly; apply dry dressing</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Granulation tissue</td><td>None noted</td><td>Document; report if develops</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tube position</td><td>Intact; external bumper in place</td><td>Verify 1–2 finger-width clearance</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Skin condition</td><td>Moist but intact; no breakdown</td><td>Dry thoroughly; apply moisture-barrier if ordered</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout callout-info" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
      <strong>👩‍👧 Family-Centered Care — Involve the Expert</strong>
      <p>Alice's mother manages this G-tube at home every single day. Ask her to demonstrate her usual care technique — this gives you important assessment data (is her technique safe?), respects her expertise, and strengthens the therapeutic relationship. Teach as you go: "I notice you do it this way — that's exactly right. One thing we can add is checking the bumper clearance each time."</p>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why does moisture from leaked formula threaten Alice's skin? What scale measures her pressure injury risk?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Why formula leakage threatens skin integrity:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Prolonged moisture exposure → <strong>skin maceration</strong> — softening and breakdown of skin tissue</li>
          <li>Macerated skin is fragile and highly susceptible to fungal infections (especially <em>Candida</em>) and pressure injury</li>
          <li>Formula contains proteins and acids that further irritate compromised skin</li>
          <li>Moist skin at the stoma site has reduced barrier function and increased friction coefficient</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Braden Q Scale (pediatric pressure injury risk assessment):</strong></p>
        <p>The <strong>Braden Q Scale</strong> is used in pediatric patients and assesses 7 subscales:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Mobility</li>
          <li>Activity</li>
          <li>Sensory perception</li>
          <li><strong>Moisture</strong> — Alice scores HIGH RISK here due to the saturated dressing</li>
          <li>Friction and shear</li>
          <li>Nutrition</li>
          <li>Tissue perfusion and oxygenation</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Interventions for moisture management:</strong> keep site clean and dry; apply moisture-barrier products (zinc oxide, petrolatum-based) if ordered; change dressings when wet; reposition to reduce pressure on stoma site; assess with every dressing change.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ The stoma is clean and the dressing is changed — now address the fever…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 4 — FEVER MANAGEMENT VIA G-TUBE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Fever Management via G-Tube</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      Alice's temperature is confirmed at 38.4°C (101.1°F). The acetaminophen PRN order requires weight-based dosing calculation before administration via the G-tube.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚖️ Weight-Based Dose Calculation</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient weight</th><td>22 kg</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Ordered medication</th><td>Acetaminophen Suspension 100 mg/mL</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Dose range</th><td>10–15 mg/kg/dose</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Minimum dose</th><td>10 mg/kg × 22 kg = <strong>220 mg</strong></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Maximum dose</th><td>15 mg/kg × 22 kg = <strong>330 mg</strong></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Dose to give</th><td><strong>300 mg</strong> (within safe range)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Volume to draw up</th><td>300 mg ÷ 100 mg/mL = <strong>3 mL</strong></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Route</th><td>Via G-tube (oral syringe)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 G-Tube Medication Administration Steps</h3>
        <ol style="font-size: 0.9rem; padding-left: 1.25rem;">
          <li>Verify the medication order in the MAR</li>
          <li>Perform the 5+ rights: right patient, drug, dose, route, time</li>
          <li>Verify patient identity with two identifiers (name + DOB)</li>
          <li>Confirm G-tube placement: aspirate for gastric contents</li>
          <li>Flush G-tube with 5–10 mL water — confirm patency</li>
          <li>Draw up <strong>3 mL</strong> of acetaminophen 100 mg/mL in oral syringe</li>
          <li>Connect syringe to G-tube port; administer slowly</li>
          <li>Flush again with 5–10 mL water to deliver full dose</li>
          <li>Clamp tube briefly; reconnect to feeding per protocol</li>
          <li>Document: medication, dose, volume, route, time, response</li>
          <li>Reassess temperature in 30–60 minutes</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout callout-info">
      <strong>💬 Therapeutic Communication with Alice During Medication Administration</strong>
      <p>"Alice, I'm going to give your tube some medicine to help bring your fever down and make you feel better. Your tube won't hurt — you'll just feel me working near your tummy for a minute. Can you hold Mr. Bear while I do this?" <em>(Use a comfort object to reduce anxiety.)</em></p>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q9: What are weight-based dosing principles for pediatric medications?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Core principle:</strong> Pediatric medications are dosed by weight (mg/kg). Using adult doses causes serious harm — overdose, toxicity, organ damage.</p>
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div>
            <h4>Acetaminophen (Tylenol)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Dose: 10–15 mg/kg/dose q4–6h PRN</li>
              <li>Max: 5 doses/24 hours</li>
              <li>Max single dose: 1000 mg</li>
              <li>For Alice (22 kg): 220–330 mg → give 300 mg (3 mL of 100 mg/mL)</li>
              <li>Watch for: hepatotoxicity with overdose</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4>Ibuprofen (Motrin)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Dose: 5–10 mg/kg q6–8h PRN</li>
              <li>For Alice (22 kg): 110–220 mg → give 200 mg (10 mL of 20 mg/mL)</li>
              <li>Watch for: GI irritation, renal effects</li>
              <li>Do NOT give to infants under 6 months</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout callout-warning" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <strong>Critical G-tube medication rule:</strong> Always use <em>liquid</em> formulations for G-tube administration. Never crush adult tablets as a substitute — concentrations differ. Verify the available concentration before calculating volume.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: When can you give ibuprofen instead of acetaminophen, and when should you alternate?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Alternating antipyretics in pediatrics:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Acetaminophen and ibuprofen act on different pathways — they can be alternated safely when fever is persistent and not controlled by one agent alone</li>
          <li>Acetaminophen: q4–6h; Ibuprofen: q6–8h — stagger timing to provide more continuous coverage</li>
          <li>Example: Acetaminophen at 8 AM → Ibuprofen at 11 AM → Acetaminophen at 2 PM</li>
          <li>Always document both medications to avoid accidental double-dosing</li>
          <li>Check for contraindications: ibuprofen is avoided in dehydration, GI bleeding, or renal compromise</li>
          <li>For Alice: acetaminophen is first choice given her G-tube and bronchitis; ibuprofen is available PRN per order if needed</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Medication given — now restart the G-tube feeding and plan care…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 5 — RESTARTING THE G-TUBE FEEDING
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Restarting the G-Tube Feeding</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      The dressing is changed, acetaminophen is given, and the G-tube is reconnected. Before restarting the enteral feeding, you perform a systematic safety check.
    </p>

    <h3>✅ Before Restarting Feeding — Safety Checklist</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Check</th><th>How to Verify</th><th>Status</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Tube placement confirmed</td><td>Aspirate for gastric contents; confirm pH ≤ 5.5 if policy requires; check external markings</td><td>Confirm ✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Gastric residual assessed</td><td>Gently aspirate; re-infuse contents per protocol; hold if &gt; facility policy limit</td><td>Assess and document</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tubing securely connected</td><td>Visually inspect connection; tug gently to ensure lock</td><td>Confirm ✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Correct formula verified</td><td>Check label against MAR — formula type, concentration</td><td>Verify ✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Correct rate confirmed</td><td>Check rate ordered against pump setting</td><td>Verify ✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td>HOB elevated 30–45 degrees</td><td>Measure or visually confirm head elevation</td><td>Position ✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Pump programmed correctly</td><td>Verify rate, volume limit, and alarm settings</td><td>Set and confirm ✓</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="info-grid" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Post-Restart Assessment</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Confirm formula flowing at ordered rate</li>
          <li>No signs of abdominal distension, discomfort, or nausea</li>
          <li>Patient tolerating feeding — no vomiting</li>
          <li>Stoma site dry; new dressing intact</li>
          <li>Monitor feeding tolerance over next 30–60 minutes</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>👥 Delegation Guidelines</h3>
        <h4 class="text-success" style="margin-top: 0;">✓ Can delegate to UAP/CNA</h4>
        <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
          <li>Vital signs recording <em>(after initial RN assessment)</em></li>
          <li>Bed linen change</li>
          <li>Hygiene assistance</li>
          <li>Reporting changes in patient condition to RN</li>
        </ul>
        <h4 class="text-danger">✗ Cannot delegate (RN only)</h4>
        <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
          <li>G-tube site assessment</li>
          <li>Medication administration</li>
          <li>Tube placement verification</li>
          <li>Patient and family teaching</li>
          <li>Documentation of clinical findings</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Pre-Sim Q4: What are the complete steps to reconnect and restart a G-tube feeding after disconnection?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Identify what happened</strong> — assess extent of disconnection; was formula lost? How long was it disconnected?</li>
          <li><strong>Stop the pump</strong> — prevent further uncontrolled formula flow</li>
          <li><strong>Assess and clean the site</strong> — remove formula residue; assess stoma skin integrity</li>
          <li><strong>Change the saturated dressing</strong> — apply clean, dry gauze or foam dressing</li>
          <li><strong>Check gastric residual</strong> before restarting — aspirate; re-infuse per policy; hold if excessive</li>
          <li><strong>Reconnect tubing securely</strong> — confirm the locking connection</li>
          <li><strong>Verify correct formula at correct rate</strong> — confirm with MAR</li>
          <li><strong>Restart the pump</strong> at the ordered rate</li>
          <li><strong>Elevate HOB 30–45 degrees</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Document thoroughly</strong>: disconnection time (estimated), site assessment findings, amount of formula lost (if estimable), dressing change, gastric residual, restart time, rate, and patient response</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

