  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-gtube">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Clinical Skills Review — G-Tube Care</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🏥 Esophageal Atresia — Background</h3>
        <p>Esophageal atresia is a congenital anomaly in which the esophagus does not form a continuous passage to the stomach. Surgical repair is performed in infancy, but many children require ongoing G-tube support for nutrition, medications, and hydration.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>G-tube (gastrostomy tube) is surgically placed through the abdominal wall directly into the stomach</li>
          <li>Allows enteral feeding and medication delivery when oral route is impaired or unsafe</li>
          <li>Alice has had her G-tube since infancy — her mother is an expert in its management</li>
          <li>Esophageal atresia patients often also have GERD (hence ranitidine)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ G-Tube Complications to Watch For</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Complication</th><th>Signs</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Tube dislodgement</td><td>Tube out of stomach; no gastric residual; formula not infusing</td><td>Do NOT reinsert without provider order; cover with gauze; call provider immediately</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Stoma infection</td><td>Redness, warmth, swelling, purulent drainage, fever</td><td>Notify provider; obtain culture; increase frequency of site care</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Granulation tissue</td><td>Pink/red fleshy overgrowth around tube</td><td>Notify provider; treatment may include silver nitrate application</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Skin breakdown</td><td>Maceration, erosion, ulceration around stoma</td><td>Keep dry; apply moisture barrier; increase dressing frequency; notify provider</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tube obstruction</td><td>Formula won't infuse; resistance on flushing</td><td>Do NOT force; try warm water gentle irrigation; notify provider if unable to clear</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Aspiration</td><td>Coughing, choking during feeding; respiratory distress</td><td>Stop feeding immediately; elevate HOB; suction if needed; notify provider</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">💊 Medication Administration via G-Tube — Key Rules</h3>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <p><strong>Never do these with a G-tube:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>❌ Crush solid adult tablets — use liquid formulations only or crushed immediate-release tablets verified as safe to crush</li>
        <li>❌ Mix medications together in the syringe — administer each separately; flush between each</li>
        <li>❌ Administer without flushing before and after</li>
        <li>❌ Restart feeding after medication without re-checking tube position and residual</li>
        <li>❌ Use IV syringes for enteral medication — use <strong>oral/enteral syringes only</strong> (cannot connect to IV lines)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>📐 Bumper Clearance Check</h3>
    <p>The external disc/bumper that sits against the skin should have <strong>1–2 finger-widths of clearance</strong>:</p>
    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-danger">Too Tight (0 finger-width)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Pressure injury at stoma site</li>
          <li>Impaired healing</li>
          <li>Tissue necrosis over time</li>
          <li>Increased infection risk</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-danger">Too Loose (&gt;2 finger-widths)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Tube migration (moving in and out)</li>
          <li>Increased formula leakage</li>
          <li>Skin irritation from movement</li>
          <li>Risk of tube falling out</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

