  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       APPENDIX D — POST-SIMULATION QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-postsim">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix D</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q1: Why is a wet G-tube dressing a high-priority nursing concern?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>A wet dressing represents a <strong>moisture-associated skin damage (MASD)</strong> risk. Prolonged skin contact with formula or gastric contents causes maceration — the skin softens, becomes fragile, and loses its barrier function. Macerated skin at the stoma site is susceptible to:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Fungal infection (especially <em>Candida albicans</em>)</li>
          <li>Bacterial superinfection</li>
          <li>Pressure injury progression</li>
          <li>Painful erosion that impairs G-tube tolerance</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Additionally, a wet dressing may indicate formula leakage — meaning the patient is not receiving their full nutritional intake, which is also a safety concern, especially in a child already ill with bronchitis.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q2: What does esophageal atresia mean, and why does Alice need a G-tube long-term?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Esophageal atresia</strong> is a congenital defect in which the esophagus does not form a complete, continuous tube from the throat to the stomach. Often associated with a tracheoesophageal fistula (abnormal connection between esophagus and airway).</p>
        <p>While surgical repair is performed in infancy, many children have:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Persistent swallowing difficulties (dysphagia)</li>
          <li>Gastroesophageal reflux (GERD) — hence ranitidine</li>
          <li>Aspiration risk — unsafe oral intake</li>
          <li>Esophageal strictures requiring ongoing dilation</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The G-tube provides a reliable, safe route for nutrition and medications that bypasses the esophagus entirely. It allows Alice to grow and develop normally while her swallowing function is managed. Her mother has become an expert in G-tube management — this family-centered expertise must be respected and incorporated into all care planning.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q3: What is the Braden Q Scale and how does it apply to Alice?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>The <strong>Braden Q Scale</strong> is the pediatric-specific version of the Braden Scale for pressure injury risk assessment. It contains 7 subscales (vs. 6 in the adult Braden):</p>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Subscale</th><th>Alice's Status</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Mobility</td><td>Moderate risk — restless but can reposition</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Activity</td><td>Moderate risk — confined to bed during acute illness</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sensory perception</td><td>Normal — Alice can communicate discomfort</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Moisture</strong></td><td><span class="badge-danger">HIGH RISK</span> — saturated dressing, formula leakage at stoma</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Friction and shear</td><td>Low risk — assisted movement in bed</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Nutrition</td><td>At risk — feeding interrupted by disconnection</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tissue perfusion/oxygenation</td><td>Adequate — SpO₂ 96%, no cardiovascular compromise</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>Alice's highest risk factor is the Moisture subscale. Interventions must focus on keeping the stoma site clean and dry, using moisture-barrier products, and increasing dressing change frequency when leakage occurs.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q4: What are the 5 rights of medication administration plus the additional rights?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Traditional 5 Rights:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Right <strong>Patient</strong> — verify with 2 identifiers (name + DOB)</li>
          <li>Right <strong>Drug</strong> — check against MAR; know the medication</li>
          <li>Right <strong>Dose</strong> — calculate weight-based dose; verify with second nurse if required by policy</li>
          <li>Right <strong>Route</strong> — G-tube requires liquid formulation; use oral/enteral syringe</li>
          <li>Right <strong>Time</strong> — administer within the scheduled window</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Additional Rights (expanded version):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Right <strong>Documentation</strong> — document immediately after administration</li>
          <li>Right <strong>Reason</strong> — understand why the patient needs this medication</li>
          <li>Right <strong>Response</strong> — assess and document the patient's response</li>
          <li>Right <strong>Education</strong> — explain the medication to patient and family in age-appropriate terms</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q5: How does family-centered care apply to a pediatric patient with a G-tube?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Family-centered care</strong> recognizes that the family is the constant in a child's life and that nurses must partner with families in all aspects of care. For Alice:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Alice's mother manages the G-tube daily at home — she is an expert and her knowledge must be respected and utilized, not dismissed</li>
          <li>Ask the mother to demonstrate her routine — this serves as an assessment AND respects her expertise</li>
          <li>Teach collaboratively: "Is there anything different about how we do it here vs. at home? Let me show you what we observe and why."</li>
          <li>Include Alice in decisions that are age-appropriate: choosing when to do the dressing change, holding a comfort object, choosing music during the procedure</li>
          <li>A 7-year-old is in Erikson's Industry vs. Inferiority stage — she needs to feel capable and involved; giving her small choices maintains her sense of control</li>
          <li>Never exclude the parent from bedside care unless absolutely clinically required</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q6: What are the developmental considerations for working with a 7-year-old?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Erik Erikson — Industry vs. Inferiority (ages 6–12):</strong> Children this age need to feel competent and productive. Involve Alice in her care; praise her cooperation.</p>
        <p><strong>Piaget — Concrete Operational Stage (ages 7–11):</strong> Alice thinks logically about concrete objects and events. Use simple, literal explanations — avoid medical jargon. Visual aids and demonstrations are effective.</p>
        <p><strong>Pain assessment:</strong> Use the Wong-Baker FACES Pain Scale — Alice can reliably point to the face that matches how she feels.</p>
        <p><strong>Communication strategies:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Ask Alice directly — do not speak only to her mother</li>
          <li>Use her name; treat her with respect; knock before entering</li>
          <li>Let her know exactly what will happen: "First I'll clean it, then I'll put on a new bandage — it won't hurt"</li>
          <li>Allow therapeutic play if available</li>
          <li>Praise cooperation: "You did a great job holding still, Alice!"</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q7: What monitoring is required for gentamicin (aminoglycoside) therapy?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Gentamicin requires careful monitoring due to its <strong>narrow therapeutic index</strong> and risk of serious adverse effects:</p>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Monitoring Parameter</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Peak and trough serum levels</strong></td><td>Draw per protocol (trough before dose; peak 30 min after infusion ends); report abnormal levels to provider</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Renal function</strong> (BUN, creatinine, urine output)</td><td>Monitor daily; hold and notify if creatinine rising — nephrotoxicity</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Ototoxicity</strong></td><td>Ask child/parents about hearing changes, tinnitus (ringing), or vertigo; report any concerns immediately</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>IV site</strong></td><td>Assess before each infusion for redness, swelling, or pain — phlebitis risk</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Infusion rate</strong></td><td>Infuse over 30–60 minutes — never IV push</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Hydration</strong></td><td>Adequate hydration reduces nephrotoxicity risk</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-warning" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <strong>Pediatric consideration:</strong> Ototoxicity can be permanent. In children, early hearing loss may impact speech and language development. Teach parents to watch for signs of hearing changes and report immediately.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Post-Sim Q8: Describe the SWIPE safety check and why it is important in pediatric nursing.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>The SWIPE safety check is a systematic environmental safety assessment performed before touching any patient:</p>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Letter</th><th>Component</th><th>Pediatric Considerations</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Siderails</td><td>Both rails up at all times for pediatric patients — children can roll out of bed; parents should not lower rails without notifying nursing</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>W</strong></td><td>Wristband</td><td>Verify with 2 identifiers; in pediatrics — name + DOB (not room number); compare with parent/guardian ID as appropriate</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>I</strong></td><td>IV lines</td><td>Assess site for infiltration, phlebitis; verify rate on pump; check label and expiration; pediatric veins are fragile — check frequently</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Pull cord / call light</td><td>Place within parent/guardian reach — a 7-year-old may not understand or be able to operate independently; ensure parent knows how to use it</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Equipment</td><td>Bed in lowest position; ensure G-tube pump alarming appropriately; clear path to bathroom; age-appropriate safety measures (crib vs. bed)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>In pediatric nursing, the SWIPE check must include parental involvement — parents are an additional safety layer and must be briefed on what they can and cannot do at the bedside.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

